title: Grateful Dead Live at The Spectrum on 1986-03-23
lineage: Dat (Sony PCM-R500) > Tascam DA-3000 > Adobe Audition CC2015 > Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/
description:
Set 1

Gimme Some Lovin'-> Deal, Hand Jive, Candyman, Cassidy, West L.A. Fadeaway, Mama Tried-> Big River-> Might As Well

Set 2

Shakedown Street-> Samson & Delilah, He's Gone-> Spoonful-> Drums-> The Other One-> Comes A Time-> Good Lovin', E: Day Job

reviews.review_text: My First Dead Show Been waiting for a long time for a SBD of this show to appear in the archive. Thanks Charlie Miller, Rob Eaton, etc.
Finally! I have waited almost 34 years to get a good SBD of the show thank you thank you thank you!!

Good show for '86, solid board This show is better on relistening than I gave it credit for at the time.  The first set smokes through Cassidy, at least.  I don't care much for the last four songs.  But Deal is a seriously scorching version, end of set quality in the second song.  

After set break, we get an average Shakedown to open the 2nd set.  Average is really darn good for that song.  Then comes a below-average Samson -- Jerry just keeps repeating the same downward pattern over and over.  He's Gone is not what I was wanting to hear at shows, and neither is Spoonful, but there's a sweet lil' jamlet in between, and then Jerry plays some tasty licks.  

Going into drums, we start to get the strange, Eno-esque sounds.  A lot of sustained high notes -- not sure if Brent is playing with the drummers or some effect Mickey's producing.  Jerry comes back and signals Other One right away, but then space dwindles down to near nothing before Jerry starts up the song proper.  No bass riff, though.  It's not the greatest Other One ever, but the recording brings Jerry through clearly, whereas, at the show, I think I must have lost him among the freaky dog-noises.  That's followed by an intense Comes a Time.  I only heard that song live twice, so it's a nice rarity.  

They finish in standard fashion, except that Bob seems to be starting into a Jesus rap in advance of Easter, talking about a guy who lived 2000 years ago who brought light into the world.  Day Job -- what can I say?

Overall a solid mid-80's performance.
